quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The border Property[/h1]

The CSS border property allows you to customize the borders of HTML elements.
In order to add a border to the element, you need to specify the [b]size[/b], [b]style[/b], and [b]color[/b] of the border. 
The example below shows how to add a solid green border to the paragraph.

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="css" ]<p>This is an example of a solid border.</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="537"]p {
   padding: 10px;    
[b]   border: 5px solid green[/b];
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2618" width="100%"]

[h1]Border Width [/h1]

The properties for the border can be set separately. The [b]border-width[/b] property specifies the width of the border.

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<p class="first">
    Border width of this paragraph is set to 2px.
</p>
<p class="second">
    Border width of this paragraph is set to 5px.
</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="538"]p.first {
   padding: 10px;    
   border-style: solid;
[b]   border-width: 2px;[/b]
}
p.second {
   padding: 10px;    
   border-style: solid;
  [b] border-width: 5px;[/b]
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2617" width="100%"]
[h1]Border Color[/h1]

The border color of the element can be defined using a color name, RGB, or Hex values. 
[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<p class="first">
   Border color has been created using <strong>color name.</strong>
</p>
<p class="second">
   Border color has been created using <strong>Hex values.</strong> 
</p>
<p class="third">
   Border color has been created using <strong>RGB values.</strong> 
</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="539"]p.first {
   padding: 10px;
   border-style: solid;
   border-width: 2px;
   [b]border-color: blue;[/b]
}
p.second {
   padding: 10px;    
   border-style: solid;
   border-width: 2px;
   [b]border-color: #FF6600;[/b]
} 
p.third {
   padding: 10px;    
   border-style: solid;
   border-width: 2px;
   [b]border-color: rgb(0, 153, 0);[/b]
} [/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2619" width="100%"]
[note] None of the border properties will have any effect unless the [b]border-style[/b] property is set.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to set the border style of the element to solid and make it 5px:
[!raw!]
p {
   {0} : solid;
   {1}: 5px;
   {2}: #FF6600;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The border-style Property[/h1]

The default value of border-style is [b]none[/b], which defines no border. 
There are various styles supported for the border-style property: [b]dotted[/b], [b]dashed[/b], [b]double[/b], etc. The example below illustrates the differences between them. 

[b]The HTML:[/b] [code format="html" ]<p class="none">This paragraph has no border.</p>
<p class="dotted">This is a dotted border.</p>
<p class="dashed">This is a dashed border.</p>
<p class="double">This is a double border.</p>
<p class="groove">This is a grooved border.</p>
<p class="ridge">This is a ridged border.</p>
<p class="inset">This is an inset border.</p>
<p class="outset">This is an outset border.</p>
<p class="hidden">This is a hidden border.</p>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b] [code format="css" codeId="540"]p.none {border-style: [b]none[/b];}
p.dotted {border-style: [b]dotted[/b];}
p.dashed {border-style: [b]dashed[/b];}
p.double {border-style: [b]double[/b];}
p.groove {border-style: [b]groove[/b];}
p.ridge {border-style: [b]ridge[/b];}
p.inset {border-style: [b]inset[/b];}
p.outset {border-style: [b]outset[/b];}
p.hidden {border-style: [b]hidden[/b];}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2620" width="100%"]
[note]In CSS, it is possible to specify different borders for different sides, using the following properties: border-top-style, border-right-style, border-bottom-style, and border-left-style for the corresponding sides.[/note]
